{"id":14881225,"mediaExerciseId":"2e9e5686-92f9-4660-b51e-029a78b926f1","exerciseName":"1","chapterName":"10","chapterTitle":"Making Capital Investment Decisions","groupId":612341,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":341,"solutions":[{"id":5669269,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this question, we are asked to define opportunity cost in the context of capital budgeting.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/18/ca5bfff834319d6ed57858d32b4fb113/2695c722e26a7113c53866b08dee1552/lateximg_large.png","width":998},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/18/ca5bfff834319d6ed57858d32b4fb113/2695c722e26a7113c53866b08dee1552/lateximg.png","width":500}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"### Opportunity cost:\n\n\nOpportunity cost in the context of capital budgeting is the potential benefit return of an investment or a project that is forgone due to a decision to select an alternative.\n\nIn simplified terms, it is the cost of what is lost when you waive a particular opportunity for another.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"58db87ef-6053-446a-bbf2-734b722d90e4","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":2},{"id":6388758,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this task, we have to explain what the opportunity cost of capital budgeting is.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The **opportunity cost** of capital budgeting is the sequential profit margin that a company completely disregards when it chooses to do using financing for such an integrated project instead of just directly investing in an established product. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"The opportunity cost is also a foundational principle in both wanting to invest and life generally. When investing, opportunity revenue is the price of profit you may well not acquire if you bought one capital asset rather than more.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"db778d74-ac34-4662-b319-2add70e044e2","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881226,"exerciseName":"2","page":341,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"20266cc1-f875-46a3-87ed-c1bd2628b6fb","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-10-critical-thinking-questions-2-20266cc1-f875-46a3-87ed-c1bd2628b6fb"},{"id":14881227,"exerciseName":"3","page":341,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"fa168c7d-70cb-45a0-b175-90af64ffd60c","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-978125991